 <a href="/content/surf-safely-sshuttle" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"><img src="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/ufiles/imagecache/teaser/nodeimage/story/11563shuttlef1.jpg" alt="" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-teaser" width="100" height="100" /></a> 
  
  


      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/surf-safely-sshuttle" title="Surf Safely with sshuttle">Surf Safely with sshuttle</a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/shawn-powers" title="View user profile.">Shawn Powers</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Oct 02, 2013 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_31 first active"><a href="/tag/security" rel="tag" title="" class="active">Security</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_196 last"><a href="/tag/tech-tips" rel="tag" title="">Tech Tips</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/surf-safely-sshuttle" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>In past articles, I've explained how to set up a SOCKS proxy with SSH. I've demonstrated how to tunnel traffic with SSH. I've even shown how to circumvent a company firewall with SSH. I've never been able to use SSH completely as a VPN, however, and that's always bummed me out—until I discovered sshuttle.<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/surf-safely-sshuttle"> more>></a></span></p>

  </div>



